Date: 23 Feb 2001
From: Pig Disease Information Centre <pdic@btinternet.com>
Source: BBC [edited

Pandemic Warning
---------------------
The head of the UN Animal Health, Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO)
warned [foot and mouth disease (FMD) had grown into a global crisis.
"We have different types of virus and one of them particularly -- type O
[the type discovered in the Essex outbreak -- is spreading and we can
really call it a pandemic," said Yves Cheneau.
Speaking on BBC Radio 4's Today program, Mr. Cheneau warned type O would
follow "not only the movement of animals but also the movement of foods, by
tourists, by immigrants and so on, and can constitute a real danger." He
added: "History shows type O started in 1991 in south Asia and spread
through the Arabian Peninsula and reached Europe for the first time in 1996."
As efforts continued to trace the source of the disease, Kevin Pearce,
spokesman for the National Farmers' Union, said vigilance and not panic
would keep the outbreak under control. "We would expect within about 7 days
we would be in a good position to know whether or not this is likely to
spread and whether we are going to see any further cases."
Further news will be posted at:
<http://www.pighealth.com/csf.htm>
