[4
Date: 23 Feb 2001
From: Patricia Doyle, PhD <dr_p_doyle@hotmail.com> and
Chris Griot <Christian.Griot@ivi.admin.ch>
Source: Reuters and UK News 23 Feb 2001 [edited

The alarming situation and fears of foot and mouth disease (FMD) spreading
in Britain has turned the countryside into a "no go" country. Hunting,
hiking and other activities have been curtailed or asked to be curtailed in
an effort to suspend the outbreak. All of Britain fears a repeat of the
1967 nightmare outbreak of FMD where more than 440 000 animals were
slaughtered after over 2300 cases were discovered
Hunting has been suspended across Britain because of the FMD outbreak. The
Countryside Alliance says the suspension will last for 7 days. The move
follows Britain's first major outbreak of the disease for 20 years.
Britain's countryside has been placed on red alert with both city and rural
dwellers told to keep away from farmland. The Ministry of Agriculture,
Fisheries and Food (MAFF) said all non-essential visits to farms with
livestock should be avoided.
"I would like to appeal to the public, particularly in the infected areas,
to minimize the risks of spread. For the public this involves reducing
contact with livestock and farms," Agriculture Secretary Nick Brown said.
The government, fearful that the disease could ruin Britain's farming
industry, is painfully aware FMD knows no boundaries and can spread easily
-- even through the air.
Postmen were among those urged to leave all deliveries at farm gates in a
bid to eliminate the risk of tramping any disease from farm to farm.
Ramblers [hikers were also asked to think about cancelling any plans for
countryside treks taking in farmland where animals were present.
Although the presence of FMD has so far only been confirmed at the Essex
abattoir where it was discovered on Monday, there are real fears it may
have spread. Officials have confirmed the animal movement exclusion zone
surrounding the Cheale Meats abattoir and farm complex, in Little Warley,
Essex, had been doubled to 10 miles.
At European Union headquarters in Brussels, experts fear the disease is so
contagious it may yet spark an outbreak on the Continent, a nightmare
scenario. In the event it happens, it could bring Europe's meat trade to
its knees.
It is not only exported livestock threatening Britain's neighbors; the
virus could also be carried by the wind, on the soles of tourists' shoes or
on the wheels of cars, [EU experts said. "This would be an absolute
disaster for the meat business, much worse than mad cow disease," said
Jean-Luc Meriaux of the EU's meat trading association UECBV.
The European Commission, meanwhile, warned it would have no hesitation in
extending the ban on Britain's 8 million-pound-a-week exports of live
animals, meat and dairy products beyond the current March 1 deadline if the
disease had not been totally eradicated.
Officials said they were chasing all possible leads for the source of the
outbreak, including the "surprisingly large" number of pet pig owners in
the affected region in southeast England.
